                'content' => '<p>While solar and wind power have dominated the renewable energy conversation, a diverse array of alternative technologies is advancing rapidly. These emerging solutions could address many limitations of current renewable systems and accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels.</p><p>Tidal and wave energy harness the immense power of ocean movements to generate electricity. Unlike solar and wind, ocean energy is highly predictable and available 24/7, providing reliable baseline power. Recent innovations in underwater turbine design and materials have improved durability and efficiency, making these technologies increasingly viable for coastal regions.</p><p>Enhanced geothermal systems are expanding the potential for earth\'s heat as an energy source beyond traditional geothermal hotspots. By injecting water into hot dry rock formations deep underground, these systems create engineered reservoirs that can generate clean power almost anywhere. The consistent output of geothermal plants makes them valuable complements to intermittent renewable sources.</p><p>Bioenergy with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) represents a promising negative-emissions technology. By growing biomass that absorbs CO2, then burning it for energy while capturing and sequestering the emissions, BECCS could actually remove carbon from the atmosphere while producing power.</p><p>Green hydrogen, produced using renewable electricity to split water molecules, is gaining attention as both an energy storage medium and a clean fuel for transportation and industry. As electrolysis technology improves and renewable electricity costs fall, hydrogen could become a crucial link in a fully decarbonized energy system.</p>',
