                'summary' => 'Exploring practical applications of blockchain technology in various industries beyond digital currencies.',
                'content' => '<p>While blockchain technology first gained prominence as the foundation for Bitcoin, its potential applications extend far beyond cryptocurrency. The core attributes of blockchain—decentralization, transparency, immutability, and security—offer solutions to challenges across diverse sectors.</p><p>Supply chain management represents one of the most promising applications of blockchain technology. By creating an immutable record of product movements, blockchain systems can verify authenticity, track ethical sourcing claims, and quickly pinpoint contamination sources in food safety incidents. Major retailers and manufacturers are already implementing blockchain to enhance transparency and build consumer trust.</p><p>In healthcare, blockchain offers secure ways to manage patient data while maintaining privacy. Distributed ledger systems can give patients control over their medical information, allowing selective sharing with providers while maintaining a comprehensive, tamper-proof medical history. This approach could reduce medical errors, eliminate redundant testing, and facilitate coordination between healthcare providers.</p><p>Intellectual property protection is another area where blockchain shows potential. Creators can register their work on blockchain platforms, establishing indisputable timestamps that prove ownership. Smart contracts can also automate royalty payments when digital content is used, ensuring creators receive fair compensation for their work.</p><p>Voting systems based on blockchain technology could address concerns about election security and transparency. Such systems would provide voters with verification that their vote was counted correctly, while maintaining ballot secrecy. Several pilot projects have tested blockchain voting in municipal elections and organizational governance.</p>',
